    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876108",
        "quote": "The rule has been that when one opens a new channel to the universe, there is usually a surprise in it. Why should the gravitational channel be deprived of this?",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876108"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Surprise",
                "url": "/topics/surprise"
            },
            {
                "name": "New",
                "url": "/topics/new"
            },
            {
                "name": "Been",
                "url": "/topics/been"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876109",
        "quote": "Observing gravitational waves would yield an enormous amount of information about the phenomena of strong-field gravity. If we could detect black holes collide, that would be amazing.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876109"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Waves",
                "url": "/topics/waves"
            },
            {
                "name": "Could",
                "url": "/topics/could"
            },
            {
                "name": "Amount",
                "url": "/topics/amount"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876110",
        "quote": "When we initially proposed LIGO, the only sources that we were really contemplating were supernovae. We thought we would see something like one a year, maybe even ten a year.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876110"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Thought",
                "url": "/topics/thought"
            },
            {
                "name": "Like",
                "url": "/topics/like"
            },
            {
                "name": "Sources",
                "url": "/topics/sources"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876112",
        "quote": "We'll have all sorts of crazy signals. And you'd be a damned fool if you didn't look for things you weren't expecting, because that's probably what you're going to see first.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876112"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Look",
                "url": "/topics/look"
            },
            {
                "name": "Going",
                "url": "/topics/going"
            },
            {
                "name": "Expecting",
                "url": "/topics/expecting"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876079",
        "quote": "It's very, very exciting that it worked out in the end that we are actually detecting things and actually adding to the knowledge, through gravitational waves, of what goes on in the universe.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876079"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Waves",
                "url": "/topics/waves"
            },
            {
                "name": "Through",
                "url": "/topics/through"
            },
            {
                "name": "Very",
                "url": "/topics/very"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876080",
        "quote": "Most of us fully expect that we're going to learn things we didn't know about.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876080"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Most",
                "url": "/topics/most"
            },
            {
                "name": "Expect",
                "url": "/topics/expect"
            },
            {
                "name": "Going",
                "url": "/topics/going"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876081",
        "quote": "We knew about black holes in other ways, and we knew about neutron stars - well, those are the two things that ultimately got seen.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876081"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "About",
                "url": "/topics/about"
            },
            {
                "name": "Other",
                "url": "/topics/other"
            },
            {
                "name": "Knew",
                "url": "/topics/knew"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876082",
        "quote": "Einstein had looked at the numbers and dimensions that went into his equations for gravitational waves and said, essentially, 'This is so tiny that it will never have any influence on anything, and nobody can measure it.' And when you think about the times and the technology in 1916, he was probably right.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876082"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Numbers",
                "url": "/topics/numbers"
            },
            {
                "name": "About",
                "url": "/topics/about"
            },
            {
                "name": "Had",
                "url": "/topics/had"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876084",
        "quote": "All at once, funding was gone due to the Mansfield Amendment, which was a reaction to the Vietnam War. In the minds of the local RLE administrators, research in gravitation and cosmology was not in the military's interest, and support was given to solid-state physics, which was deemed more relevant.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876084"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Local",
                "url": "/topics/local"
            },
            {
                "name": "Amendment",
                "url": "/topics/amendment"
            },
            {
                "name": "Cosmology",
                "url": "/topics/cosmology"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876085",
        "quote": "The field equations and the whole history of general relativity have been complicated.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876085"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "General",
                "url": "/topics/general"
            },
            {
                "name": "Been",
                "url": "/topics/been"
            },
            {
                "name": "Equations",
                "url": "/topics/equations"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876086",
        "quote": "I didn't understand the Weber bar and how gravitational waves interacted with it. I sat and thought about it over a weekend, trying to prepare for the lecture for the following Monday. I asked myself how would I do it. The simplest way... was a thought experiment.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876086"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Thought",
                "url": "/topics/thought"
            },
            {
                "name": "Weekend",
                "url": "/topics/weekend"
            },
            {
                "name": "Prepare",
                "url": "/topics/prepare"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876087",
        "quote": "We were looking almost one-tenth of the way to the edge of the universe. We're planning to use the facilities we have to make improvements by another factor of 10... a strain sensitivity that is 10 times smaller. This means looking 10 times further out into the universe.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876087"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Use",
                "url": "/topics/use"
            },
            {
                "name": "Almost",
                "url": "/topics/almost"
            },
            {
                "name": "Smaller",
                "url": "/topics/smaller"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876088",
        "quote": "By the time we made the discovery in 2015, the National Science Foundation had put close to $1.1 billion into it.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876088"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Made",
                "url": "/topics/made"
            },
            {
                "name": "Had",
                "url": "/topics/had"
            },
            {
                "name": "By The Time",
                "url": "/topics/by_the_time"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876089",
        "quote": "Gravitational waves, because they are so imperturbable - they go through everything - they will tell you the most information you can get about the earliest instants that go on in the universe.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876089"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Waves",
                "url": "/topics/waves"
            },
            {
                "name": "Through",
                "url": "/topics/through"
            },
            {
                "name": "Will",
                "url": "/topics/will"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876090",
        "quote": "Over years, the noise level will be brought down, and LIGO will be three times better and see three times farther.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876090"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Over",
                "url": "/topics/over"
            },
            {
                "name": "Level",
                "url": "/topics/level"
            },
            {
                "name": "Brought",
                "url": "/topics/brought"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876091",
        "quote": "All of this technology wasn't available to Einstein. I bet he would've invented LIGO.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876091"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Technology",
                "url": "/topics/technology"
            },
            {
                "name": "Bet",
                "url": "/topics/bet"
            },
            {
                "name": "Available",
                "url": "/topics/available"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876092",
        "quote": "Receiving money for something that was a pleasure to begin with is a little outrageous.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876092"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Money",
                "url": "/topics/money"
            },
            {
                "name": "Pleasure",
                "url": "/topics/pleasure"
            },
            {
                "name": "Receiving",
                "url": "/topics/receiving"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876093",
        "quote": "We haven't found anything that we can't explain at all. I hope that will happen.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876093"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Happen",
                "url": "/topics/happen"
            },
            {
                "name": "Explain",
                "url": "/topics/explain"
            },
            {
                "name": "Found",
                "url": "/topics/found"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876094",
        "quote": "We're going to be seeing things from regions in the universe where Einstein is the whole story. Newton you can forget about.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876094"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Going",
                "url": "/topics/going"
            },
            {
                "name": "About",
                "url": "/topics/about"
            },
            {
                "name": "Regions",
                "url": "/topics/regions"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876095",
        "quote": "The concept of what we're looking for is so important. The fact that the effect is tiny is just our misfortune.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876095"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Important",
                "url": "/topics/important"
            },
            {
                "name": "Fact",
                "url": "/topics/fact"
            },
            {
                "name": "Tiny",
                "url": "/topics/tiny"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876096",
        "quote": "It's a spectacular signal. It's a signal many of us have wanted to observe since the time LIGO was proposed. It shows the dynamics of objects in the strongest gravitational fields imaginable, a domain where Newton's gravity doesn't work at all, and one needs the fully non-linear Einstein field equations to explain the phenomena.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876096"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Explain",
                "url": "/topics/explain"
            },
            {
                "name": "Observe",
                "url": "/topics/observe"
            },
            {
                "name": "Objects",
                "url": "/topics/objects"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876098",
        "quote": "This is the first real evidence that we've seen now of high gravitational field strengths: monstrous things like stars moving at the velocity of light, smashing into each other, and making the geometry of space-time turn into some sort of washing machine.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876098"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Some",
                "url": "/topics/some"
            },
            {
                "name": "Other",
                "url": "/topics/other"
            },
            {
                "name": "Monstrous",
                "url": "/topics/monstrous"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876099",
        "quote": "The whole idea of gravity curling up space, that is the epitome of what is going on in a black hole. I would've loved to have seen Einstein's face if he were presented with the data that we actually discovered such a thing, because he himself probably didn't believe in much of it.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876099"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Data",
                "url": "/topics/data"
            },
            {
                "name": "Epitome",
                "url": "/topics/epitome"
            },
            {
                "name": "Discovered",
                "url": "/topics/discovered"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876100",
        "quote": "A gravitational wave is a very slight stretching in one dimension. If there's a gravitational wave traveling towards you, you get a stretch in the dimension that's perpendicular to the direction it's moving. And then perpendicular to that first stretch, you have a compression along the other dimension.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876100"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Very",
                "url": "/topics/very"
            },
            {
                "name": "Slight",
                "url": "/topics/slight"
            },
            {
                "name": "Other",
                "url": "/topics/other"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876101",
        "quote": "Space is much stiffer than you imagine; it's stiffer than a gigantic piece of iron. That's why it's taken so damned long to detect gravitational waves: to deform space takes an enormous amount of energy, and there are only so many things that have enough.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876101"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Why",
                "url": "/topics/why"
            },
            {
                "name": "Gigantic",
                "url": "/topics/gigantic"
            },
            {
                "name": "Detect",
                "url": "/topics/detect"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876102",
        "quote": "Many of us on the project were thinking if we ever saw a gravitational wave, it'd be an itsy bitsy little tiny thing; we'd never see it. This thing was so big that you didn't have to do much to see it.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876102"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Thinking",
                "url": "/topics/thinking"
            },
            {
                "name": "Project",
                "url": "/topics/project"
            },
            {
                "name": "Big",
                "url": "/topics/big"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876103",
        "quote": "The students on my course were fascinated by the idea that gravitational waves might exist. I didn't know much about them at all, and for the life of me, I could not understand how a bar interacts with a gravitational wave.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876103"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Students",
                "url": "/topics/students"
            },
            {
                "name": "About",
                "url": "/topics/about"
            },
            {
                "name": "Idea",
                "url": "/topics/idea"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876104",
        "quote": "I said, suppose you take a light - I was thinking of just light bulbs because, in those days, lasers were not yet really there - and sent a light pulse between two masses. Then you do the same when there's a gravitational wave. Lo and behold, you see that the time it takes light to go from one mass to the other changes because of the wave.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876104"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Changes",
                "url": "/topics/changes"
            },
            {
                "name": "Other",
                "url": "/topics/other"
            },
            {
                "name": "Mass",
                "url": "/topics/mass"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876105",
        "quote": "If the wave is getting bigger, it causes the time to grow a little bit. If the wave is trying to contract, it reduces it a little bit. So, you can see this oscillation in time on the clock.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876105"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Grow",
                "url": "/topics/grow"
            },
            {
                "name": "Contract",
                "url": "/topics/contract"
            },
            {
                "name": "Bigger",
                "url": "/topics/bigger"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876106",
        "quote": "Every time you accelerate - say by jumping up and down - you're generating gravitational waves.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876106"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Waves",
                "url": "/topics/waves"
            },
            {
                "name": "Say",
                "url": "/topics/say"
            },
            {
                "name": "Jumping",
                "url": "/topics/jumping"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876111",
        "quote": "Over and over in the history of astronomy, a new instrument finds things we never expected to see.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876111"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "New",
                "url": "/topics/new"
            },
            {
                "name": "Never",
                "url": "/topics/never"
            },
            {
                "name": "Over",
                "url": "/topics/over"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876066",
        "quote": "What was done is measure directly, with exquisitely sensitive instruments, gravitational waves predicted about 100 years ago by Albert Einstein. These waves are a new way to study the universe and are expected to have significant impact on astronomy and astrophysics in the years ahead.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876066"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Ahead",
                "url": "/topics/ahead"
            },
            {
                "name": "Study",
                "url": "/topics/study"
            },
            {
                "name": "About",
                "url": "/topics/about"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876083",
        "quote": "The obvious thing to me was, let's take freely floating masses in space and measure the time it takes light to travel between them. The presence of a gravitational wave would change that time. Using the time difference, one could measure the amplitude of the wave.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876083"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Space",
                "url": "/topics/space"
            },
            {
                "name": "Wave",
                "url": "/topics/wave"
            },
            {
                "name": "Would",
                "url": "/topics/would"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876062",
        "quote": "You know the Einstein waves can be thought of as a distortion of space and time. But the way we see it, we see it as a distortion of space. And space is enormously stiff. You can't squish it; you can't change its dimensions so easily.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876062"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Waves",
                "url": "/topics/waves"
            },
            {
                "name": "Thought",
                "url": "/topics/thought"
            },
            {
                "name": "Stiff",
                "url": "/topics/stiff"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876074",
        "quote": "The fact that this radiation is so penetrating - nothing stops it - makes it so you can look for things that you have never seen before, and you can look at things you know in a way that's new. That is really the big step forward.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876074"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "New",
                "url": "/topics/new"
            },
            {
                "name": "Fact",
                "url": "/topics/fact"
            },
            {
                "name": "Big",
                "url": "/topics/big"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876097",
        "quote": "The triumph is that the waveform we measure is very well represented by solutions of these equations. Einstein is right in a regime where his theory has never been tested before.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
            "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876097"
        },
        "topics": [
            {
                "name": "Triumph",
                "url": "/topics/triumph"
            },
            {
                "name": "Very",
                "url": "/topics/very"
            },
            {
                "name": "Been",
                "url": "/topics/been"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "url": "/quotes/rainer_weiss_876056",
        "quote": "My parents were singularly uninterested in me. My father was too self-centered and too busy with his own practice to pay a lot of attention to me, and my mother was probably deflected more by my sister.",
        "author": {
            "name": "Rainer Weiss",
